[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(9, 10) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And when those beasts . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And whensoever the living beings shall give",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the future is used) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "glory and honour and thanks to Him who sitteth upon the throne, to Him who liveth to the ages of ages, the four-and-twenty elders shall",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (as is their wont) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fall down before Him who sitteth on the throne, and worship Him that liveth unto the ages of ages, and shall",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (as is their wont) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cast their crowns before the throne",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "saying",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ... It is not to Him who sat upon the throne, but to Him who sitteth there, as he liveth to the ages of ages, that this homage is paid. The future tense ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "(shall ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "give glory, &c.) implies the eternal repetition of the act. The connection between the praise given by creation, and the consequent homage of the twenty-four elders, expresses a truth. The Church of Christ does not always hear the voice of praise from created things. Often the creation groaneth” and travaileth; but her chorus of praise rises when she perceives that “every thing that hath breath praiseth the Lord.” The converse of this thought — the earth bringeth forth her fruit when the people praise God—is hinted in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 67:5-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “the earth ceases her travail when the sons of God are made manifest (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 8:19-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Crowns.—The crowns are not royal crowns, but the crowns of conquerors. These are laid down before the throne by those who overcame, not in their own might, but through the blood of the Lamb (Revelation 12:11; comp. Revelation 7:14).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Crowns.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The crowns are not royal crowns, but the crowns of conquerors. These are laid down before the throne by those who overcame, not in their own might, but through the blood of the Lamb (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 12:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 7:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Revelation 4:9-11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Revelation 4:9-11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when those living creatures give glory, &c., the elders fall down ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, as often as the living creatures begin their song of adoration and praise, the elders immediately fall down. The expression implies that they did so at the same instant, and that they both did this frequently. The living creatures do not say directly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Holy, holy, holy art thou; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "but only bend a little, out of deep reverence, and say, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Holy, holy, holy is the Lord. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But the elders, when they are fallen down, say, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou art worthy, O Lord, to receive glory ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— This he receives, not only when he is thus praised, but also when he destroys his enemies, and glorifies himself anew; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "glory, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — In the Greek, (which has the article with each noun,) it is, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the glory, and the honour, and the power; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "answering the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thrice holy ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "living creatures, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For thou hast created all things ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— By thine almighty energy. Creation is the ground of all the works of God. Therefore for this, as well as for all his other works, he must and will be praised to all eternity. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And for thy pleasure ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Δια το θελημα σου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "on account of thy will; they are ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— They exist; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "at first ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "created ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Their first production and continued existence are owing to the riches of thy free goodness; and therefore they are all under the strongest obligations, according to their respective natures, to subserve the purposes of thy glory. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4:9-11 All true believers wholly ascribe their redemption and conversion, their present privileges and future hopes, to the eternal and most holy God. Thus rise the for-ever harmonious, thankful songs of the redeemed in heaven. Would we on earth do like them, let our praises be constant, not interrupted; united, not divided; thankful, not cold and formal; humble, not self-confident.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And when those beasts give glory ... - As often as those living beings ascribe glory to God. They did this continually ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and, if the above explanation be correct, then the idea is that the ways and acts of God in his providential government are continually of such a nature as to honor him. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9-11. The ground of praise here is God's eternity, and God's power and glory manifested in the creation of all things for His pleasure. Creation is the foundation of all God's other acts of power, wisdom, and love, and therefore forms the first theme of His creatures' thanksgivings. The four living creatures take the lead of the twenty-four elders, both in this anthem, and in that new song which follows on the ground of their redemption (Re 5:8-10).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "when—that is, whensoever: as often as. A simultaneous giving of glory on the part of the beasts, and on the part of the elders.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "give—\"shall give\" in one oldest manuscript.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for ever and ever—Greek, \"unto the ages of the ages.\"",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
