  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "9, 10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when those beasts",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] Read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And when the living creatures shall give glory and honour and thanks to Him that sitteth upon the Throne, to Him that liveth for ever and ever, the four and twenty elders shall fall down before Him that sitteth …, and shall worship Him …, and shall cast.…”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The meaning of the futures is doubtful: some take it as “implying eternal repetition of the act.” Or the meaning may be (if one may say so reverently) a sort of stage direction: “during the future course of the vision, these (who never leave the scene) are to be understood to be thus employed.” But it is always a question in this Book whether the use of tenses be not accommodated to the rules of Hebrew rather than Greek grammar: the sense may after all be merely frequentative.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cast their crowns",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Alford compares Tac. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ann.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " XV. xxix. 3, 6, where Tiridates lays down his crown before the image of Nero, as a token of homage for his kingdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 4:9-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ὅταν δώσουσι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πεσοῦνται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Each future expresses a simultaneous act of giving of glory on the part of the beasts and on the part of the elders: and, at the same time, it has a frequentative force: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "As often as the beasts give glory, immediately the elders fall",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And when those beasts give",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and as often as the living belongs shall give.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The expression has a frequentative force, and also points to a continued repetition of the act in the future; perhaps a contrast to the past, since before the redemption the Church, as being of the whole world, could not join in the adoration. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Glory and honour and thanks",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Eucharistic hymn recognizes the glory and honour which are the inseparable attributes of God, and renders the thanks due to him from his creation. To him that sat on the throne, who liveth forever and ever; or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to him sitting on the throne.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Triune God (see on ver. 2). \"Who liveth forever and ever\" declares that attribute which was ascribed to God, in the song of the living beings, by the words, \"which was, and is, and is to come\" (see on ver. 8). Revelation 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When (ὅταν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Whensoever, implying, with the future tense, the eternal repetition of the act of praise.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Give (δώσουσιν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., as Rev., shall give. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
